segments.text: The number of college courses that they had to have before they were accepted into vet school increased at a very rapid rate.
Did this mean that while you were on the student selections committee, it appeared that the students were improving, or did it seem to have any effect at all?
The students who were
selected as a rule were the ones who had more to show.
They had more courses.
Naturally, you're going to take someone who has more to offer to you.
If he has a degree, so much the better.
And if his work has been good work, excellent work,

in the four years well that's that's much more valuable than just a two-year student much more valuable if you've had four years of good grades instead of two years unless this person is a very brilliant person with two years and he is he has made almost a four point grade point ratio in the two years
And he comes well-qualified, well-recommended, and you talk to instructors he's had on the campus or wherever he went, and they have recommended him very highly.
Well, you place a person like that up against a four-year person, if the four-year person, say, had maybe B's or C's in his chemistry or biology or something like that.
I see.
Yeah, because to me, unless they made good in their science courses, unless they were strong in science and mathematics, I didn't want them.
I see.
Chemistry.
Is that how your colleagues on the committee felt?
They all felt the same way about it.
Now, Dr. Davis liked to use the computer.
I don't know why.
I don't understand all I know about a computer anyway.
Well, Dick got with the people over in the computer area, and they devised a method.
You'd have to get him to tell you.
I wouldn't know.
But anyway, we had reams and reams of material from the computer.
And Dick would evaluate them, every angle that he could think of, and put it through the computer and come out with a list.
a computerized list.
Well, usually the thing would tally pretty well with what we had selected.
Anyway, yeah.
Yeah.
But we used that to sort of substantiate if we had to have any argument.
So I think it worked out very nicely.
It worked out very nicely.
There were some students who
Well, we've had some very good students who were not very proficient in English.
And they made a very poor showing on interview.
Their language was horrible.
And they just fell completely out there.
I remember one fellow.
He was worse than some of our athletes with, you know,
He couldn't say anything but you know.
Otherwise his grades were good.
He didn't get in.
He wore us out with you know, you know, you know.
He couldn't say a word, a phrase or maybe a sentence without you knows.
I just watched an interview the other night and I heard exactly that same thing.
Yes, I did too.
with a basketball player.
And I thought, this is a shame.
You know where they get it?
I don't know where they get it, but they sure do say it.
This young man began to work there in the College of Veterinary Medicine in the photographic lab.
And I did quite a bit of work down there preparing my neurology notebook, which I want to show you.
We had to get photographic.
equipment to do this.
Back then when we started out in anatomy, you didn't have any photographic equipment.
You begin with the gross brain here.
That's an old cow's brain.
She's been knocked in the head.
There's blood all over the lower part of her brain here in the olfactory area, but here's a side view and so on.
Well, we went, here's a
top, sagittal section, and then you start with the spinal cord, and go on up, go on up here, motor and UTI.
Oh, those are excellent.
And on through.
Now, who put this book together?
I did.
Oh, really?
That's an outstanding.
I did all the photography.
I didn't know you were an expert at that.
See, you go clear on through the brain stem.
Just section, section, section.
You're up in the medulla oblongata now.
Here's the inferior olive pyramidal tracts.
So on.
Just clear on up.
Just section by section.
See?
Clear on through the whole brain stem.
Here the oculomotor nerves there.
Third nucleus in here.
And so on.
Clear on through it.
And you leave a page in here for the student to make a note.
Now, we had class sets.
And these sections tallied with their class sets.
I did the sectioning.
Brain stem, these are big sections, about like eight.
And you've got to have a good sharp knife and know what you're doing.
And Mrs. Craig, my technician, did the staining.
It's a special Kluver stain.
where the myelin sheath of your nerve fiber stains black, see?
There's fiber tracks.
These are nuclei, all these light areas, substantia nigra here, and so on.
And the student then, I would project the slide on the screen and point out everything to him.
And he is sitting there with his microscope, and he has this section in his set.
And he follows.
Excellent idea.
Yeah.
Follows right along.
He can take his notes right here.
He can say number one is the medial geniculate body.
He can put a one here.
Great idea.
And he's got it to study.
And then when he's through, here we go.
We're getting on up in the brain stem now.
Oh, I think that there's maybe one more.
But anyhow, and they say, well, you didn't write anything.
Well, I wrote a dissertation.
I did a dissertation, and I studied 21,000 sections of turkey brain and seven brains that I had dissected.
And I cut, sectioned, and stained, and did the whole work.
You never did turn out much in the way of papers writing.
What time did I have to write or carry on research?
Who sharpened all the microtome knives?
I was the only one who ever learned how to sharpen a microtome knife.
And the day I retired, I sharpened some knives for Miss Craig so she'd have some good sharp knives to go with.
Well, that's a great little booklet.
That's tremendous.
So you do all of your photography.
You do everything.
But you took those pictures?
I took everything.
I did all the sectioning.
What kind of camera did you use?
We had a micro camera.
The lenses would enable you to put a 3x2 slide on there with a section.
And you can get the whole thing with it.
You have a view screen up here.
You get it in focus.
Then you slide your cassette in here with your film and you take the picture.
You have your lamps and everything.
But anyhow, that's the way it was.
There's a question I was interested in.
Instead of having
two or three men in the department to handle about as many students as they have now, while you have 10 or 12.
I should have had that during the speed-up program and during the time Dr. Dunn was out when I was bacteriology and pathology, post-mortem and everything.
There's something I was interested in, and that is
In the 1960s, we had applicants of about 140 or 150 a year, but now we have like 600 people applying to get into med school, or vet school here.
What a tremendous increase, and I was wondering what your opinion of why.
Well, we had those back in the 60s.
We had four, five, 600 applicants.
Oh, why has it become so popular?
I couldn't tell you.
I really don't know.
I don't know.
I guess the big thing is you can make money, and that seems to be what the student wants now, something he can make money with and be his own boss.
I would venture to say that in human medicine, it's the same way.
In law, it's the same way.
In dentistry.
They are out for what they can make.
They want to be rich.
They want to be independent.
Did you want that when you were a student?
I wanted a living.
See, I'm a depression person.
And I was thankful to get a job that paid me $1,500 on a nine month basis.
I was also very thankful to get a graduate assistantship at $45 a month because otherwise I couldn't have gone.
No way.
The first woman was admitted here in vet school in 1963, and now they comprise about one-third, one-third of the student body.
37 and Dr. Burns' little book.
Do you have one of Dr. Burns' history?
Yeah.
Well, he has a tabulation there.
Were you on this, you were on this Elections Committee?
Yeah, Ms. Oliphant came, yes.
We were very happy with her.
What transpired?
She came very well, recommended by one of the veterinarians she'd worked for down there in the valley, and she was
A little wrangler herself.
This old boy said, whenever I have a mean horse to break, I get her to break it.
Really?
Yeah.
What's her name?
What's her name?
Oliphant.
Her name was Oliphant.
Yeah.
She married an old boy.
I've forgotten.
Lee, I believe, was his name.
And he was taking veterinary medicine, too.
Anyway, she was all right.
She was a good student.
She carried her into the stick.
I don't believe we've had very many girls who have fallen down.
They've all done all right.
Why did we change from an all-male school to allowing women?
Well, the women wanted in veterinary medicine.
The pet angle especially practiced with cats and dogs, small animals.
That appealed to them.
I guess their motherly instincts.
It worked out all right, as far as I know.
Is there any pressure from President Rutter or any other administrator?
No.
I don't recall any pressure.
This Miss Oliphant came, she was admitted on the basis of graduate student.
Veterinary medicine was considered then more of a graduate course.
Well, I still think it is.
I think it's actually veterinary medicine is graduate school, as far as I'm concerned.
Just like in Galveston, old Dr. Sinclair said to us, you're in graduate school.
Well, I feel the same way about veterinary medicine.
It's graduate school.
Do you think there was much resistance with your colleagues about having ?
I couldn't see any resistance in veterinary medicine to admission of women.
What was the quality of the women who applied back in the early 1960s compared to the men?
Well, women got in and those we took were as well qualified as the men.
Because they were people or women who had had
or they had had contact with animal life for a long time, and they were well motivated.
This is what they wanted, and that's all they wanted.
Was there a direct impact after you let women in?
I mean, did you change the curriculum?
Were there any changes because of that?
No, no.
No, unless they work, unless they study hard.
No, they're not going to make it.
Another thing concerning the so-called minorities, another thing that interests me, not only women, but throughout the years.
We've had two blacks that I know of up to the time.
Why don't they apply?
I don't know.
I don't know why.
We had one black who failed in his anatomy.
He went on to Meharry Medical College and graduated as an MD.
We had another black from Galveston, Texas, his mother
This is in the 1960s?
Yeah, his mother was a maid in a motel.
This old boy came out of the Marine Corps.
He had been a corporal.
I think Rank was a corporal in the Marine Corps.
He came to A&M and took veterinary medicine.
He had a hard time.
But that old boy was trying.
He was struggling.
And I think that...
Well, I'm sure that he had to repeat some courses.
But he finally made it, and he's practicing veterinary medicine in California now.
He was a swell fella.
Yeah, great big guy.
Well built, like little Abner.
But he made it.
He had trouble, but he made it.
He just bit it off and didn't spit it out.
He stayed with it.
You had to admire that rascal.
Were there very many who applied when you were on the selections committee?
No.
A strange thing.
I don't know why.
I guess they found out that it was so difficult, I suppose.
But yet there are many of them in human medicine.
But veterinary medicine somehow or other just doesn't appeal.
And I don't know why it is.
It would seem to me that if a person is reared on a farm, as many of them were, that they would be interested in veterinary medicine, in animals.
But that's not the case.
We would like to have some real good students in the minorities.
It's the same way with the Spanish-Americans.
We've had a few.
Most of them we've had have been real good students.
I don't know, but maybe a handful of Latin Americans.
But they've been good students.
In fact, I think we have one out there now.
Out of the veterinary corps, he became a colonel.
What's his name?
Trevino, Trevino, he finally got, he has a PhD in pathology, and so on.
He's on the staff now?
Yeah, he's retired from the veterinary corps, he's on the staff now, yeah.
Oh, good for him.
But a good student, excellent.
Now as far as research is concerned at Texas A&M, I was wondering what you considered to be the strengths and the weaknesses of the,
research in the vet school?
Well, actually in anatomy, what research we did was laughable.
Well, actually we didn't do very much.
It was more of a teaching department.
It was more of a teaching department as long as I was with it.
But they are doing research now.
We were beginning before I left.
But up to that time, I think you could say we were building.
Yeah.
What were the great research institutions by the time you left in the early 1970s?
In the A&M?
No, no.
What were the great in the country?
Well, you'd have to put it down to medical schools mostly.
I don't think veterinary schools were doing very much.
I don't recall.
Cornell, probably, and Michigan State, Iowa State, to me, were outstanding.
Or maybe Minnesota.
Put Minnesota in there.
But not Texas A&M.
This is a more recent development.
You see, up to as long as we had a division of veterinary science.
in the experiment station.
All of the research work was done there.
In fact, that's all they did, was all they were supposed to do.
They did the research.
We did the teaching.
And this went on up to as long as Dr. Schmidt was there in veterinary research.
Dr. Turk, who was parasitology head for so long, he started out.
been there, science, Dr. Schmidt, and so on.
Well, that's the way it was, and up until the time that D.W. Williams came on as vice president, and was he president?
D.W. Or just acting.
Anyhow, he started the breakdown of the
research in one area and teaching in the other.
He wanted it mixed up.
He was the one who, as far as I know, began breaking it down so that we'd have research and teaching.
I think it's come quite a ways.
I know they have maybe a $300,000 research program in anatomy now.
In monkeys?
Well, we were beginning.
I know we were beginning to make brain stem sections and spinal cord sections of baboons and different types of monkeys so that we would be prepared if we needed to study
anything in the central nervous system, we'd have sections of central nervous system for comparison to any pathology or anatomical changes.
Well, I'm well pleased that they have an opportunity, and I'm pleased, too, that we have sufficient faculty.
Right, to carry on.
When you had two or three men in your teaching, good heavens.
No, nine different courses, don't forget it.
Impossible.
Now, the archives put me up to this question, and I don't know anything about this group, but they said I should ask you because you might.
And that is, during the 1950s, I guess, there was a group called the True Texans, the Tonqua tribe?
The Tonqua tribe.
Can you tell me about them?
I don't know anything about these people.
Well, Dr. Morgan called me one day and asked me if I wouldn't be on a committee to try some of these students who were found out to be Tawankawa tribes.
He said, we need some good Aggies.
Well,
I said, yes, I don't mind being on the committee.
So I was.
Penberthy was chairman.
They had put a, what would you call him?
A person had joined the TTs and was making their meetings.
And he got a hold of the little black book, the registry.
where they're supposed to sign their names in blood and all that.
And you'd be surprised that the names were read out at the meeting, people who belonged to the TTs.
Well, as a military school, we were not supposed to have any fraternities, secret societies.
Felborden?
No, no.
But evidently they had two.
the Tawankawa tribes and the Swastikas.
Yeah.
So.
This is after the Second World War, the Swastikas?
Yeah.
And then before the war, this goes way back.
I know way back in the 20s, they still had the Tawankawa tribe and the Swastikas.
It was named long before Hitler.
I don't know whether they kept the Swastikas after Hitler came on the line.
But the TTs were here.
In fact, I suppose the TTs have been around since A&M began.
I have an old captain's chair over here that came out of the old chemistry lecture room.
A picture was taken in 1904.
And I want to show you something that's carved on the arm.
You're talking about the TTs?
We're lucky here.
You see a TT there?
That's their sign.
That's their brand.
That's their brand.
It's Texas Tech now, but the Toronto tribe there.
And that old chair came from the Kim lecture room.
And I have a picture that was taken in 1940.
These old captain's chairs in there.
It was in the old amphitheater.
in the old chemistry building that stood where the library, the Cushing Library was built.
What was their function, or what was their purpose?
Well, when they read off the list of names, I found out that an old B Troop cavalry, my captain was a T.T.
His top kick was a TT.
The colonel of the cadet corps was a TT.
And I don't know how many colonels of the cadet corps that were read off through the years were TTs.
And evidently, it was playing a part in military appointments.
I know I had one.
When I was a freshman, there was a senior who played football.
He led it.
But he told me, he said, Fish, I want to tell you something.
You're going to be around here several more years.
But unless you belong to a secret fraternity, an organization like that, you're not going to amount to anything.
He said, I don't belong.
But I had an awful time making a letter.
Said the guys who were fraternity men made letters.
But I had an awful time.
That old boy is dead now, too.
Well, what did the TTs believe in?
Well, to me, it was more of a social organization.
They had dances and such as that and parties off campus.
So.
Had to be wealthy, didn't it?
Well, they had to be socialites in a way.
They had to.
Why did they name themselves the True Texans?
I don't know.
I don't know where the name Tawanka was.
It wasn't True Texans.
It was Tawanka with tribe.
Oh.
So True Texans is not the name.
Well, one of the members of that committee

was a TT and he was common of the cadet he was common of cadets at A&M old Joe Davis he went he went from here to uh Stephenville to Tarleton in general then it was a social organization or a social club and
And in fact, from the reading off of the names, I don't know what's ever become of the little black book, but the chairman of the board of directors of Texas A&M College's name was read off.
And at that time, he was chairman of the board.
Did you ever join?
No, sir.
Why not?
I wasn't a socialite.
I didn't have money.
Oh, and I didn't intend to graduate from A&M either.
I was going to take my pre-med and go on, which I did, but I came back.
But I will say this for the TTs.
They were made up of good men.
And when I went back, the dean of the College of Veterinary Medicine at that time

was a his name was read off too out of the little black book and was this just for students or was it for it was just for students it was just for students and then many of these people had aspired on yeah i don't know where the little black book went as far as i'm concerned why the tt was made up of damn good men because i didn't know that it wasn't a name it was read off it wasn't an outstanding personality
And all I can say is hooray for the TTs.
Does it still exist today?
They were supposed to break up that year.
What year was that?
Disband.
Oh, I don't know when Dr. Morgan was president back in there in the 60s.
It wasn't Bill Armistead was dean.
It was... Oh, don't you have a... Well, let's see.
Yeah, I can find out when that was, yeah.
Mm-hmm.
Oh, I don't know.
They said yes.
Why did they investigate?
